Could try:

R W Byrne ('The thinking ape' or 'Human cognitive evolution')

Krebs has a good article from 98 'The evolution of moral behaviour'
which is in 'Handbook of Evolutionary Psychology: Ideas, Issues and
Applications'

Tooby and Cosmides have a large number of odds and sods out there -
haven't read a great deal of their stuff though so a bit of a sift
might be an idea.  A lot of it is about culture and evolution.

de Waal has already been mentioned.  You might also want to look up
specific subject elements such as 'theory of mind' as this does have
some bearing on how we might perceive ourselves and compare to other
animals (primates especially).

Whenever looking at EP though I'd recommend bringing a large dose of
salt.  There is also a difference between biological origins and EP
although the line is blurred a lot of the time.  Biology and
psychological issues focus more on the physical brain and nervous
system rather than the possible evolutionary pathways that could lead
to social organisation.

EP does have some insights but is tenuous at best - neither does EP
provide much beyond suggesting a framework for the establishment of
negotiated structures like morality, religion etc.
