I don't think that the &quot;good of the group&quot; can be sustained by the concept
of evolution.  It is, however, a reflection of the fact that social animals
have evolved so that individual survival often depends on membership in a
group.  The evolution of  wolf packs is an emergent property of the survival
of individual wolves that benefit from being pack members.  A wolf pack can
bring down a large cervid whereas a lone wolf might starve or be fatally
injured attempting to kill a large animal.  Individual behaviors that
facilitate group living are positively selected, what we can describe as
'morality' is actually a property of the inherent social behaviors of the
individual animals.
