This doesn't follow. Most tetrapods walk. Does that mean that we don't
need the word &quot;walk&quot;?

Much behavior (how humans eat, for example) does not fall in the moral
realm. The word is useful for distinguishing between the two. Also, it
may be that people used to judge other animals' behavior by human
standards. (&quot;That dog is an adulterer!&quot;)

If social animals have competing drives (do I eat this food and risk
being ostracized, or do I share this food and improve my chances for
reproduction), it might be called something like moral and selfish.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; What qualifies a behavior as moral?
">

Does it follow the local tribe's rules for moral behavior? I suspect
there is an inner core of behavior which is genetically shaped, given
a childhood within certain healthy parameters. We seem predisposed to
think that stealing from, or killing, members of one's own tribe is
wrong. It seems clear that growing up in a violent or chaotic
environment encourages the expression of more directly self-serving
behavior.

Morality is also tied up with *polite behavior, which is much more
variable and complex. Maybe it has to do a lot with tribal identity
(&quot;*Decent people excuse themselves from the table before they leave
it, Jonathon.&quot;)

Moral behavior is largely behavior that is good for the tribe.

In the 21st century, behavior is judged partly on how well an
individual can expand his concept of &quot;tribe&quot; to include a wider
circle.

